<h3 class="govuk-heading-m" id="assistive-technology-testing">
  Assistive technology testing
</h3>
<p>
  Each page needs to be tested with assistive technology devices. These are tools 
  such as screenreaders, screen magnifiers and speech recognition software.
</p>
<p>
  WCAG 2.1 outlines that websites must be robust and work on a range of assistive 
  technologies. It does not specifically state which ones, but we should assume a 
  range includes screenreaders, screen magnifiers and voice recognition as a minimum.
</p>
<p>
  Some assistive technology requires a licence, but most devices have them built in and 
  you can also get some for free. You can meet the <a href="/section/accessibility-and-the-law/accessibility-regulations">
  accessibility regulations</a> using these tools, but if you're working to the 
  GOV.UK Service Standard you will need to make sure your service works on very 
  particular technologies. You can <a href="https://www.gov.uk/service-manual/technology/testing-with-assistive-technologies">
  read more about assistive technology testing and the GOV.UK Service Standard</a>.
</p>
